<TITLE> Govt to see new education policy on Sep 2 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Mustak Ahmed bdnews24.com correspondent Dhaka, Aug 24 (bdnews24.com)A 16-member committee will hand the new National Education Policy to the government on Sep 2, recommending the extension of primary level to class eight and secondary to twelve, an official said on Monday. Quazi Kholiquzzaman Ahmed, co-chair of the National Education Policy Formulation Committee, told bdnews24.com, "We are now close to the end. The policy will be submitted to the education minister on Sep 2." Ahmed said the committee was suggesting extension of primary and secondary levels. "It's included to the final recommendations." A previous draft report by the committee suggested extending primary education to eight years - from class one to eight. It would be implemented gradually, six years by 2012, seven years by 2015 and eight years by 2018. The committee also suggested extending secondary education to class twelve, from the current class ten. Education minister Nurul Islam Nahid announced formation of the policy-making body headed by professor Kabir Chowdhury on April 8, tasked with introducing a modern education plan in line with guidelines prepared by the previous Awami League administration. The committee includes writer and science teacher Dr Muhammad Zafar Iqbal, vice-chancellor of the Open University Dr RIM Aminur Rashid and Jahangirnagar University's Prof Shaheen Kabir. It was asked to submit a final report by 90 days, but the committee's first meeting was held on May 3, 25 days after its formation. Accordingly, the submission date was extended to Aug 3. The committee sought another month's extension of the deadline just before the submission date. The latest extension ends on Sep 3. bd
